al scheme in terms of which we think about social groups, collective action, social convention, and shared belief. [It] offers an important corrective to individualistic thinking in the social sciences."--Michael Root, Philosophical Review "In this rich and rewarding work, Margaret Gilbert provides a novel and detailed account of our everyday concepts of social collectivity. In so doing she makes a seminal contribution to . some vexed issues in the philosophy of social science. [An] intellectually pioneering work."--John D. Greenwood, Social Epistemology  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCollective behavior. 0aSocial action. 0aSocial groups. 0aSociologyxMethodology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aBurge, Tyler.  aDescartes, Rene.  aDouglas, Jack.  aGauthier, David.  aGilbert, Margaret.  aHarman, Gilbert.  aKripke, Saul.  aLewis, David.  aMacIntyre, A.  aPlato.  aQuinton, Anthony.  aSchiffer, Stephen.  aTaylor, Charles.  aVon Mises, Ludwig.  aWeber, Max.  aanthropology.  aassociational obligations.  acoextensive social groups.  acommon knowledge.  aeconomic classes.  aevaluability condition.  ajoining a social group.  amysticism.  anatural necessity.  anorms.  aparticipant agency.  apolitics: elections.  aprecedent.  aquestioning.  asecrecy situation.  atravelling together.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691214627zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691214627423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691214627.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACK